sect2.para:
Contemporary models of worry view worry as avoidance behavior (Sibrava & Borkovec,
            2006
         ). Information about the first component is usually not apparent, including the controlling stimulus and the reflex-like response that presumably serves as the antecedent in the second component. That is, worry appears to serve an avoidance function, but it is often not clear what the client is avoiding. Many clients report that their worry episodes are preceded by “down time,” periods when there are fewer demands on them, and/or periods when they felt bored. Consistent with that observation
            observation
         , some theorists have suggested that worry prevents sudden changes in negative affect levels by maintaining a relatively consistent, moderately high level of anxiety, avoiding dramatic shifts in anxiety (Newman & Llera, 
            2011
         ). Others have proposed that worry distracts the individual from feelings of uncertainty (Koerner & Dugas, 
            2006
         ). We have observed that clients presenting for treatment of severe worry symptoms are often experiencing significant transitions, perhaps triggering existential concerns. The diagnostic criteria for GAD do not make reference to the controlling stimuli (cues and triggers) of worry.
